"# Chapter 5 — Power supplies

Every circuit needs power. Somewhere upstream, energy is coming
out of a battery, a wall adapter, a bench supply, or a USB port.
Somewhere on the board, that energy is being distributed to
every chip that needs it. The wires and pours that carry the
power are called rails. The wire everything comes back to is
called ground.

That last sentence is the deep one. Motoi wants you to hold it:
**current is a loop.** It leaves the source, goes through the
circuit, and comes back. Ground is the return path. If ground is
broken, current cannot flow, and nothing works.

## Rails

The 'positive rail' is the wire that carries +V. The 'negative
rail' or 'ground rail' is the wire that carries 0V or -V. On a
breadboard, they are the long strips along the top and bottom.
On a PCB, they are wide traces or entire copper pours.

Common rails:

- **+5V** — the classic hobbyist voltage. USB provides it.
  Most TTL chips want it. Arduino Uno runs on it.
- **+3.3V** — the modern lower voltage. Most microcontrollers
  released after about 2010 run on it. Lower power, faster
  switching. ESP32, Raspberry Pi Pico, most modern MCUs.
- **+12V** — used by fans, some motors, some old analog
  circuits.
- **+/-15V** — analog dual rail. Op-amps often want this.
- **Battery voltage** — whatever your battery is. LiPo: 3.0
  to 4.2V per cell. AA alkaline: 1.5V per cell nominal, 1.0V
  when tired.

A power supply's job is to hold its rail at the target voltage
regardless of what the load is doing. A cheap unregulated
supply won't. A regulated one will. If you build anything
sensitive, you want regulated. If you build something rugged
that doesn't care about a few tenths of a volt, unregulated is
fine.

## Ground

Ground is a name for a specific node in your circuit that
everything else is measured against. It is not literally the
Earth (unless you're doing high-voltage work, in which case it
sometimes is). It's just: 'this is the zero.'

Sometimes there are multiple grounds — analog ground, digital
ground, chassis ground — and they need to be tied together at
exactly one point to avoid ground loops. That is beyond a first
book on shop-talk, but the concept is worth naming.

The critical rule: every part of your circuit that returns
current has to see ground somehow. If a chip has a VCC pin
connected and a ground pin floating, the chip is not powered.
It might partially work through parasitic paths. It might
smoke.

## Bypass capacitors

Also called decoupling capacitors. Small ceramic caps, usually
0.1μF (100nF), placed physically close to a chip's power pins,
one leg on VCC and one leg on ground.

Why they matter: chips draw current in short bursts as their
internal transistors switch. If the rail is far away, the wire
between the rail and the chip has inductance, and inductance
resists sudden changes in current. That means the chip briefly
sees a voltage dip when it needs current in a hurry.

The bypass cap is a small local reservoir. It supplies the
sudden current so the chip doesn't have to reach all the way
back to the main rail for a burst. This keeps the local
voltage stable.

Rule of thumb: one 0.1μF bypass cap per chip, placed within a
few millimeters of the power pin. For chips that draw a lot,
add a bigger bulk cap (1μF, 10μF) nearby too. Datasheets
usually tell you what they want.

## Ground planes and star grounds

On a well-designed PCB, one whole layer is a solid copper
pour connected to ground. Every 'via' from the signal layer
drops through to ground with almost no impedance. This is
called a ground plane, and it makes low-noise circuits much
easier to build.

For beginner breadboard work, a ground plane isn't available.
You just make sure every ground pin gets to the ground rail
by a short, direct wire. Don't route ground through six
components in series.

## What happens when ground is bad

Bad ground shows up as:

- Circuit works when you touch the ground wire and stops when
  you let go.
- Digital signals become noisy or unreliable.
- Analog signals pick up hum from nearby power lines (50 or 60
  Hz, depending on your country's grid).
- Chips get hot without doing anything.
- Nothing seems to work but there's no obvious reason.

If you find yourself troubleshooting a circuit and half the
symptoms are weird, check ground first. Continuity test from
every part's ground pin to the supply's ground terminal. If
any of them beeps only faintly or not at all, you found it.

## A tiny worked model in Motoi Scheme

Voltage on a rail with a load pulling current, plus a bypass
cap smoothing spikes. Simplified model:

```
;; Rail voltage under load: V_rail = V_supply - I_load * R_wire
;; where R_wire is the resistance of the trace between supply
;; and load.

(define (rail-voltage v-supply i-load-amps r-wire-ohms)
  (- v-supply (* i-load-amps r-wire-ohms)))

;; 5V supply, 100 mA load, 0.5 ohm wire:
(rail-voltage 5.0 0.1 0.5)   ;; => 4.95  (0.05V drop — fine)

;; Same wire, but a chip briefly pulls 2A during a switching event:
(rail-voltage 5.0 2.0 0.5)   ;; => 4.0   (1V drop! chip resets)

;; With a bypass cap, the cap supplies the burst locally,
;; so the wire only sees the average. Load stays at 4.95.
```

That is what a bypass cap prevents: the rail dropping to 4V
briefly and the chip resetting or misreading. The math is
simple. The physical placement is the thing.

## What Motoi can and cannot do here

Motoi cannot check your ground. Motoi cannot poke your rail with
a probe. Motoi cannot see if you left the ground clip off. What
Motoi can do: walk you through the concept. Talk you through
what to check with your meter. Explain why the bypass cap goes
where it does. Tell you the rule of thumb.

If your circuit is behaving weirdly, he'll ask you: 'Is the
ground solid? Have you checked continuity from every ground
pin to the supply?' That is the first-question shape.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Rails carry the pressure. Ground carries the return. Current is
a loop. If any part of the loop is broken, nothing works. Bypass
caps hold the rail steady near each chip when the chip needs a
burst.

Simple ideas. Load-bearing every time.")
